Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

>> I don't think it's ever safe to clear this flag. And even if it could be made safe, I don't think that clearing it is a good way to solve any problem.

> John, could you explain better please. we can handle that totally internally to OSD, meaning no exposure for LOHA_EXISTS at all - then the users would need to call some method (like dt_attr_get()) to get -ENOENT, but that's probably too radical at the moment.

It doesn't match that existing logic around this flag. As an example we have lots of code of the form


if (!lu_object_exists(obj))
        return -ENOENT;

if (IS_REG(lu_object_attr(obj)))
        /* Something */


Now all of this code is dangerous because LOHA_EXISTS is being cleared somewhere else.

> And Alex also thought LOHA_EXIST is overused somehow.

Please find out exactly how before adding another flag. We have LU_OBJECT_HEARD_BANSHEE, LOHA_EXISTS, DEAD_OBJ, opo_non_exist, and what else? How many such flags (with often unspecified or loose semantics) do we need?

Patch Set 6:

> John, LOHA_EXISTS being clear doesn't really change much as it doesn't control object's existence, it only "caches" that state.

Yes but we have code that assume it's never cleared once set.


if (!lu_object_exists(obj))
        RETURN(-ENOENT);

...

mode = lu_object_attr(obj);

Recall that lu_object_attr() will assert that the object exists. I don't see any locking to protect this.

> a private flag in OSD which is used only by OSD is fine, IMHO. personally I'd like to get rid of LOHA_EXISTS at all, but that's a big project.

Yes. Either we have oo_inode or we don't. Then we use locking and error handling.
